<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n01118o"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n01" href="#n01118o">N01 (VI.B.10)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n01all.htm#n01118o"> 118(o)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> eventuated in</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[USES AND ABUSES OF LOTTERIES. Dublin Gambling Romances.]</font> <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> Mr. Frank Thorpe Porter relates in his &ldquo;Reminiscences of a Dublin Police Magistrate&rdquo; that an extensive book-seller in Dublin had formed a connection with the house of Rish and Co. in Cornhill by which he was enabled to do a profitable business in bills in London among the Dublin merchants, and also to deal largely in the tickets and shares of the State lotteries. &ldquo;One evening,&rdquo; writes Mr. Porter, &ldquo;in the year 1794 my father had occasion to call on this gentleman and found him unusually dissatisfied. He said that Rish&apos;s people had made a great mistake in sending him several whole lottery tickets instead of quarters, eighths, or sixteenths, and that these lottery tickets had been left on his hands, involving a loss of sixty pounds.&rdquo; There was not time to communicate with London before the drawing day, and he could only warn them against committing a similar error on the next occasion. However, in about a week after my father ascertained that the mistake had <mark>eventuated in</mark> one of the tickets turning out a prize for twenty thousand pounds. Rish was no longer censured by the man whose wealth, previously considerable, had received a great and unexpected augmentation <small> <a name="IT27jan23" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#IT27jan23"><cite title="source">Irish Times</cite></a> (27 January 1923) 10/6</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Raphael transcription: <a name="c05167p" href="c05all.htm#c05167p">VI.C.05:167(p)</a> </mm></dd> </dd></dl>
